        "## Exercise 2: Theoretical Foundation\n",
        "\n",
        "**Closed-form solution.** The transaction-cost-adjusted problem is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\omega_{t+1}^{*} := \\arg\\max_{\\omega:\\,\\iota'\\omega=1}\n",
        "\\;\\omega'\\hat\\mu_t - \\tfrac{\\gamma}{2}\\,\\omega'\\hat\\Sigma_t\\omega\n",
        "- \\lambda\\,(\\omega-\\omega_t^{+})'\\hat\\Sigma_t\\,(\\omega-\\omega_t^{+}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Expanding the quadratic TC term and collecting like powers of $\\omega$ yields an equivalent standard MV problem with modified inputs $\\tilde\\mu_t := \\hat\\mu_t + 2\\lambda\\hat\\Sigma_t\\omega_t^{+}$ and $\\tilde\\gamma := \\gamma+2\\lambda$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\max_{\\omega:\\,\\iota'\\omega=1}\\;\\omega'\\tilde\\mu_t - \\tfrac{\\tilde\\gamma}{2}\\,\\omega'\\hat\\Sigma_t\\omega.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The first-order condition with Lagrange multiplier $\\phi$ for the budget constraint gives $\\tilde\\mu_t - \\tilde\\gamma\\hat\\Sigma_t\\omega^* - \\phi\\iota = 0$, so\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\boxed{\n",
        "\\omega_{t+1}^{*} = \\frac{1}{\\tilde\\gamma}\\hat\\Sigma_t^{-1}(\\tilde\\mu_t-\\phi\\iota),\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\phi = \\frac{\\iota'\\hat\\Sigma_t^{-1}\\tilde\\mu_t - \\tilde\\gamma}{\\iota'\\hat\\Sigma_t^{-1}\\iota}.}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Convex combination.** Substituting $\\tilde\\mu_t = \\hat\\mu_t + 2\\lambda\\hat\\Sigma_t\\omega_t^+$ into the solution and noting that the same Lagrange multiplier $\\phi$ satisfies $\\iota'\\omega^{\\mathrm{MV}}=1$ for the standard MV portfolio $\\omega^{\\mathrm{MV}} = \\frac{1}{\\gamma}\\hat\\Sigma_t^{-1}(\\hat\\mu_t - \\phi\\iota)$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\omega_{t+1}^{*}\n",
        "= \\underbrace{\\frac{\\gamma}{\\tilde\\gamma}}_{\\alpha}\\,\\omega^{\\mathrm{MV}}\n",
        "+ \\underbrace{\\frac{2\\lambda}{\\tilde\\gamma}}_{1-\\alpha}\\,\\omega_t^{+},\n",
        "\\qquad \\alpha + (1-\\alpha) = 1,\\quad \\alpha,1-\\alpha\\in(0,1).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Hence $\\omega^*_{t+1}$ is a **convex combination** of the mean-variance portfolio and the pre-rebalancing portfolio $\\omega_t^+$.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Role of $\\lambda$.** The parameter $\\lambda$ governs the trade-off between chasing the optimal MV portfolio and staying put. As $\\lambda\\to 0$, $\\omega^*\\to\\omega^{\\mathrm{MV}}$ (no cost of rebalancing); as $\\lambda\\to\\infty$, $\\omega^*\\to\\omega_t^+$ (never rebalance). Larger $\\lambda$ produces lower turnover but also larger deviation from the unconstrained optimum.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Realism of the variance-based TC model.** Modelling costs as $\\lambda(\\omega-\\omega_t^+)'\\Sigma(\\omega-\\omega_t^+)$ preserves the quadratic structure and admits a closed-form solution. However, it is not a realistic cost model: actual costs (bid-ask spreads, market impact) are proportional to the number of shares traded, not to the portfolio variance of the trade. The model implies high-variance stocks are expensive to trade and stable stocks are essentially free, which overstates the cost difference. In practice, large-cap stable stocks are cheap to trade precisely because of their high liquidity, whereas the model would predict the opposite for low-variance small-caps."
